1
00:00:00,220 --> 00:00:10,974
Agent Quarantine is a local command firewall for AI coding agents.
It isn't a sandbox. Think of it as a practical safety layer between
an agent and your shell.

2
00:00:11,494 --> 00:00:21,971
Here's the basic idea. Common tools go through lightweight path
shims. Dangerous commands are blocked, risky ones pause for
approval, and every decision is logged.

3
00:00:22,491 --> 00:00:32,626
Here's the first example. An agent downloads a remote script with
curl and pipes it straight into a shell. Agent Quarantine blocks it
before anything can run.

4
00:00:33,146 --> 00:00:42,727
The same applies to secrets. A read-only command can still be
dangerous when it points at a dot env file, an SSH key, or another
credential.

5
00:00:43,247 --> 00:00:54,235
Before the agent starts, preflight checks the repository too. Here,
it catches an NPM lifecycle script, and an instruction designed to
override the safety rules.

6
00:00:54,755 --> 00:01:02,267
Afterward, the report command turns the session log into readable
Markdown, so you can see exactly what was blocked and why.

7
00:01:02,787 --> 00:01:12,730
One important limitation: this isn't a virtual machine or a kernel
sandbox. Binaries called by absolute path can still bypass path-
based shims.

8
00:01:13,250 --> 00:01:23,727
For an unfamiliar repository, Agent Quarantine gives you a practical
first layer: one that stops common dangerous commands and leaves a
clear audit trail.
